Architecture Diagram – Application Load Balancer (AWS)

                🌍 Internet (Users)
                         │
                         │ HTTP (Port 80)
                         ▼
                ┌───────────────────────┐
                │  Application Load     │
                │  Balancer (ALB)       │
                │  Public Subnet A      │
                │  Public Subnet B      │
                └─────────┬─────────────┘
                          │
                Target Group (HTTP : 80)
                          │
          ┌───────────────┴───────────────┐
          │                               │
          ▼                               ▼
 ┌───────────────────┐         ┌───────────────────┐
 │   EC2 Instance 1  │         │   EC2 Instance 2  │
 │   Private Subnet  │         │   Private Subnet  │
 │   AZ A            │         │   AZ B            │
 │   Web Server      │         │   Web Server      │
 │   (User Data)     │         │   (User Data)     │
 └───────────────────┘         └───────────────────┘


🔐 Security Groups

ALB Security Group:
- Inbound: HTTP (80) from 0.0.0.0/0
- Outbound: HTTP to EC2 Security Group

EC2 Security Group:
- Inbound: HTTP (80) ONLY from ALB Security Group
- Outbound: Allow all (default)


🧠 Key Flow (Step-by-Step)

1. User visits ALB DNS name
2. Request hits ALB (public)
3. ALB listener (HTTP:80) receives request
4. ALB forwards request to Target Group
5. Target Group routes to healthy EC2 instance
6. EC2 returns response (different content per instance)
7. ALB sends response back to user


❤️ Health Checks

- Path: /
- Protocol: HTTP
- ALB checks each EC2 instance
- Unhealthy instances are removed from rotation


🚫 Important Rule

- EC2 instances are NOT publicly accessible
- Only ALB can talk to EC2


